# arvo-mask-contracts. Design

The mask trait surface. One trait declaration: `Mask<const W: u8>`.
Concrete impls live in `arvo-bitmask`. Consumers writing
mask-generic code bind to this surface to keep their transitive
dependency footprint small. `#![no_std]`, no alloc.

Depends on `notko`, `arvo-storage`, `arvo-bits-contracts`.

## Mask

```rust
pub const trait Mask<const W: u8>: Sized + Copy {
    fn empty() -> Self;
    fn full() -> Self;
    fn set(self, idx: USize) -> Self;
    fn clear(self, idx: USize) -> Self;
    fn test(self, idx: USize) -> Bool;
    fn count(self) -> USize;
    fn union(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn intersection(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn difference(self, other: Self) -> Self;
    fn complement(self) -> Self;
    fn mask_for_width(n: USize) -> Self;
}
```

`W` is the mask width (number of bits the mask covers). Default-method
bodies compose `BitLogic` from `arvo-bits-contracts`. Concrete impls
in `arvo-bitmask` (`Mask64` for W=64, `Mask256` for W=256, etc.) supply
the storage and may override defaults with hardware-specific
implementations.

`mask_for_width(n)` produces a mask with the lowest n bits set.
Consumed by `Narrow<T>` impls to truncate a wider raw to fit a typed
container.

